31:40.000 --> 31:55.000
And I think that what happens is that in the way we have mainly lived for thousands and thousands of years is in harmony with nature, in harmony with society, in harmony with the myths, the rituals, the beliefs of our culture.

31:55.000 --> 32:10.000
And that these had been ample ways of alerting us to many kinds of truth that was not just a kind of tit for tat in the court of law way of debating things, but certain realities could not be encompassed in that way.

32:10.000 --> 32:12.000
But they didn't need to be.

32:12.000 --> 32:31.000
Well, what's happened in a largely deracinated culture where people have been torn away from their communities, dragged into the cities, more and more into a world made by machines, reflecting the left hemisphere as kind of a world all around them.

32:31.000 --> 32:48.000
They look out of the window, they see mechanisms, they see hard surfaces on a rigid grid, and they are no longer in touch with what I'm honored and grateful to be in touch with here, which is being surrounded by nature.

32:48.000 --> 32:51.000
And these things teach you, they speak to you.

32:51.000 --> 33:00.000
And so I think what's happened is that in this world in which we rely very much on discourse, you have to choose what it is you say.

33:00.000 --> 33:13.000
The first thing is that the right hemisphere's story is much more complex than that of the left hemisphere, and therefore requires a lot of effort to articulate, as I know, because I've articulated it at very great lengths in those two books.

33:13.000 --> 33:27.000
And a lot of people write to me and say, I mean countless people write to me and say, thank goodness, you've explained something that kind of knew at some level, but I just had no way of working it out, expressing it or defending it.

33:27.000 --> 33:36.000
And so I think what happens is that you have to make decisions, and the worst thing that can happen to you nowadays is to be said to be inconsistent.

33:36.000 --> 33:43.000
In fact, there's a great deal of wisdom in sometimes being inconsistent, because it's usually more than one side to a question.

33:43.000 --> 33:47.000
In fact, if only we realized that there's always more than one side to a question.

33:47.000 --> 33:57.000
We wouldn't have all the ridiculous self-righteousness, foot stamping, hysterical fit on the internet when somebody says something that somebody else doesn't agree with.

33:57.000 --> 34:01.000
Well, get real, get educated, this is what life is like.

34:01.000 --> 34:13.000
And so there's a kind of idiocy and ignorance that is spread across mass culture, which encourages black and white thinking, the loss of all the nuances.

34:13.000 --> 34:19.000
And in the process, all the subtle stuff is drowned out by sound bites.

34:19.000 --> 34:29.000
And I could say something which, if taken in context, meant almost exactly the opposite of what it would seem to be saying if it was just a sound bite taken out of its contact.

34:29.000 --> 34:37.000
And so incredible injustice is done to many people by something being taken out of context and whizzed around the world.

34:37.000 --> 34:44.000
And then next thing, they find that people are sort of treating them as a non-person.

34:44.000 --> 34:56.000
So we're involved in this process of distancing from nature and coming more and more into, well, I guess they are machine environments.

34:56.000 --> 34:59.000
They've been machines, they are somewhat machine-like.

34:59.000 --> 35:02.000
We can go back to a movie like Metropolis for its language.

35:02.000 --> 35:03.000
Wonderful.

35:03.000 --> 35:05.000
The whole city is a big machine.

35:05.000 --> 35:06.000
Yes.

35:06.000 --> 35:08.000
And that's 100 years ago.

35:08.000 --> 35:09.000
Yes.

35:09.000 --> 35:13.000
Now, we've advanced on a lot from there.

35:13.000 --> 35:19.000
So can we talk a bit about myth directly, I guess?

35:19.000 --> 35:30.000
Firstly, could I ask you, what are your formative mythic influences, like myths maybe that you grew up with or that are important to you?

35:30.000 --> 35:32.000
That's a good one.

35:32.000 --> 35:49.000
Well, I certainly didn't have a religious upbringing, not at least until I went to secondary school, where I was fortunate to be introduced to something I thought was beautiful and resonant and deep.

35:49.000 --> 35:53.000
So what did I find?

35:53.000 --> 35:56.000
I think my father was very literalistic.

35:56.000 --> 35:57.000
Bless him.

35:57.000 --> 36:03.000
I mean, he was a good man, a very good man, but he didn't have much time for poetry or music or anything like that.

36:03.000 --> 36:05.000
He liked facts.

36:05.000 --> 36:09.000
And I'm in favour of facts too, a lot of them.

36:09.000 --> 36:16.000
And I've defended my point of view with them, but I think there's more to life than that.

36:16.000 --> 36:24.000
Robert Graves' The White Goddess, actually, was a book I read in my teens, and I thought it was really, really important.

36:24.000 --> 36:37.000
I also read Helen Waddell's The Wandering Scholars, which was about the flourishing of poetry, music and dance in the late Middle Ages in Europe and what this meant for the culture.

36:37.000 --> 36:42.000
And then I didn't really follow the path.

36:42.000 --> 36:50.000
To this day, I haven't read The Hobbit and I haven't read The Lord of the Rings, and it's not that I don't think, you know, I don't respect Tolkien, I do.

36:50.000 --> 36:59.000
It's just rather, as I say, I don't these days have so much time for reading, you know, mythological books.

36:59.000 --> 37:12.000
I remember when I used to go say with my grandparents, I was encouraged to, and in those days we did, as we were told, to go and lie down after lunch, which gave them a chance to have a little nap and a bit of a rest.

37:12.000 --> 37:20.000
And in my bedroom, beside my table, there was a book, The Myths of Greece.

37:20.000 --> 37:32.000
And so I familiarised myself with Greek myths early on, and they were very, they touched me deeply, along with these Celtic myths that I'd heard from Robert Graves.

37:33.000 --> 37:36.000
And so these things were very important to me.

37:36.000 --> 37:46.000
And then later, you know, as I say, well, not later, but in my teens, I began to become intrigued and exploring further the mythos of Christianity.

37:46.000 --> 37:50.000
I mean, a word I use without any implication of this being true or false.

37:50.000 --> 38:00.000
And indeed, I think that myths have a kind of truth which is greater than factual truth, which as I say was a perception of the ancient Greeks anyway.

38:00.000 --> 38:06.000
So these are the things that have really intrigued me.

38:06.000 --> 38:14.000
And I also read, I did read the C. S. Lewis Narnia books, partly because I'd read the last battle when I was at school.

38:14.000 --> 38:24.000
But then when I had children of my own, I read them the whole Narnia seven-part thing, and they were completely rapt fired.

38:24.000 --> 38:29.000
And so was I, you know, I was thinking, fuck you, this is good stuff.

38:29.000 --> 38:35.000
So those are the things that, you know, it more or less obviously have populated my imagination.

38:35.000 --> 38:45.000
I was surprised when you said that you didn't have these things until a little bit later in your life.

38:45.000 --> 38:56.000
Because now it seems, I think many people are searching for something that they find in myth, and maybe you did that searching as well.

38:56.000 --> 39:14.000
And I think one of the problems with our perception of myth, and especially maybe the Christian mythos, is the idea that's held now that if you went back 300 years, everyone fully believed in Christ or in God or in the elements of the mythos.

39:14.000 --> 39:26.000
When, in fact, I think it's always been a thing that people have searched for, and a few people have found, rather than the actual held belief of everyone.

39:26.000 --> 39:33.000
The holding of fixed belief with certainty is not part of faith. It wouldn't be faith if it was certain.

39:33.000 --> 39:37.000
Faith is a matter of fidelity, in fact, that's the root of the word.

39:37.000 --> 39:49.000
In other words, it's something that you give your loyalty to, because you think it's great and noble, and it will lead you to places of revelation, of illumination, and enlightenment.

39:49.000 --> 40:02.000
And I think there's always been this tendency to think that signing up to six impossible things before breakfast is what religion is about, but it is not at all.

40:02.000 --> 40:19.000
It's about enriching the way in which you see the entirety of the world, so that once you start to see the world with different eyes, it has meaning, it has direction and purpose, it has beauty and truth in it.

40:19.000 --> 40:28.000
And these are the things that really seem to me to be the essence of a fulfilling life. Not to have those things is to be set adrift.

40:29.000 --> 40:43.000
This is backed by scientific research, but it's also intuitively obvious that the things that give us a sense of meaning are not invented by us, but are contacted by us.

40:43.000 --> 40:58.000
We are able to perceive them, and these are things we perceive with the help of nature, with the help of an intact tradition of a society, and through religions, or at any rate through a spiritual inclination.

40:58.000 --> 41:04.000
And these things are all opposed to the machine. There's no place in them for the mechanical, the simply mechanical.

41:04.000 --> 41:25.000
The simply mechanical is far too crude, leaves almost everything that's of important out. And so while it's useful, undeniably, it's only as good as the use is to which it's put, and often we're not the wisest assessors of what's going to happen when we start using it in a certain way.

41:25.000 --> 41:39.000
And we're already finding that we've set in motion things that we cannot now easily stop. It's the story of the Sorcerer's Apprentice, you know, who knew how to utter the spell that would cause the machine to get going, but doesn't know how to stop it.

41:39.000 --> 41:53.000
And now there's a lot of people who are warning us about the way in which this is going to impinge on humanity and perhaps take, if I may put it this way, the humanity out of humanity.

41:53.000 --> 42:12.000
So I think these things are massively important. And to embrace that mythos of Christianity is not to force yourself to believe anything, but to listen, to open your heart and mind to what is expressed for me most powerfully through the arts that it has generated.

42:12.000 --> 42:33.000
And so through the quite extraordinarily beautiful music, particularly of the Renaissance, and the extraordinarily fine paintings and the very moving poetry, and these things make clear to us things that otherwise we would ignore.

42:33.000 --> 42:45.000
That's my idea in a nutshell that it's not surprising that we're highly stressed, depressed, anxious, don't know what we're doing, don't know where we're going, because we've chucked all the means towards meaning out.

42:45.000 --> 42:54.000
I just want to emphasize again, you know, lots of people say, oh yes, you need these things like you make them up. Actually, you're in a padded cell, you can't see anything.

42:54.000 --> 43:02.000
It's a horrible business and the sooner it's over, the better. But let's cheer ourselves up along the way by pretending that there's something out there.

43:02.000 --> 43:11.000
No mate, there is something out there and we're part of it, by the way. Nature is not out there. Nature is in here and I am in nature.

43:11.000 --> 43:21.000
And the divine realm is not something out there or up in the sky. It's something that's in here and I'm in it. And society is not something other than me.

43:21.000 --> 43:25.000
I am in society and society is in me. These are the ways to say.

43:25.000 --> 43:44.000
But when people try to turn to something like the Christian mythos, maybe it's fair to say that what they get first is that left-brained literal interpretation of the mythos, which is in its way dogmatic.

43:44.000 --> 43:52.000
And they're meeting that with their own left hemisphere interpretation, which is where the arguments come up from.

43:52.000 --> 44:01.000
So I don't want to give this to you because this starts to become a bit like a guru question, I guess.

44:01.000 --> 44:09.000
But how do we then reconnect with our right hemisphere? That's a too big a question, I think.

44:09.000 --> 44:26.000
But maybe just in that mythic sense, when someone is asking that question, well, the Minotaur doesn't literally exist or we don't have any historical evidence for X or Y.

44:26.000 --> 44:29.000
What is an answer to that, do you think?

44:29.000 --> 44:41.000
Well, not everything that is very real is tenable down. It's not capable of being fixed.

44:41.000 --> 44:50.000
The left hemisphere wants things that are fixed and it can fix them in language and it can fix them by tracing a course in history.

44:50.000 --> 44:57.000
But while that is a very useful idea, don't get me wrong, I don't disparage that, I use that all the time.

44:57.000 --> 45:04.000
My mind is quite wrathful, actually. But it also realizes, using reason, that reason is not everything.

45:04.000 --> 45:11.000
And Pascal himself said, reason is feeble indeed if it cannot explain that reason is not everything.

45:11.000 --> 45:25.000
And of course, for people who like scientific and mathematical proofs, Gödel's theorem actually proves that there are things that are certainly true within a certain framework but cannot be proved within that frame.

45:25.000 --> 45:35.000
So I think one needs to free oneself from the idea that one builds up a picture of reality from little nuggets that one puts together.

45:35.000 --> 45:39.000
Well, I've got a fact there and a fact there, I put them here. Of course, they don't seem to mean anything.

45:39.000 --> 45:47.000
Well, no, first of all, you've taken them out of context. They only mean something in the context that there is.

45:47.000 --> 45:54.000
And so we need that business of bringing together, but it doesn't start from the bits.

45:54.000 --> 46:00.000
It starts from the fact that things are already here and that our mind wants to break them up.

46:00.000 --> 46:08.000
So one has to think in broader patterns over greater distances in time and in space.

46:08.000 --> 46:20.000
So we are connected with others across time and space. We are as connected with our ancestors as we are with our descendants.

46:20.000 --> 46:25.000
And we have loyalties to both and duties to both.

46:25.000 --> 46:34.000
And we're also connected to people all around the world as we more and more perceive through the damage that has been done by industrialization.

46:34.000 --> 46:41.000
And so I think the first thing is to perceive the world differently.

46:41.000 --> 46:46.000
Often in a religion, people will say, and they're right.

46:46.000 --> 46:52.000
To me, say a Christian, it's not to believe the following things and never doubt them.

46:52.000 --> 46:58.000
But it is to see with new eyes, to feel with a new heart.

46:58.000 --> 47:03.000
There is a medieval prayer, which I think is very important, God be in my head.

47:03.000 --> 47:09.000
And it's very short. It's only a few lines. You know, God be in my head and in my understanding.

47:09.000 --> 47:13.000
God be in my eyes and in my looking. God be in my mouth and in my speaking.

47:13.000 --> 47:18.000
God be in my heart and in my thinking. God be at my end and at my departing.

47:18.000 --> 47:27.000
And that very neat and short poem is very much about what I was talking about, internalizing something that is bigger than you.

47:27.000 --> 47:30.000
And so the first thing is to change the cast of mind.

47:30.000 --> 47:34.000
And people might say, well, how do I do that without working from step to step?

47:34.000 --> 47:39.000
But that, again, is the left hemisphere. This is actually not the way things work.

47:39.000 --> 47:50.000
Many things come as a moment of insight, as an aha moment, a re-jigging of a shape of a form, so that you see it anew.

47:50.000 --> 48:01.000
And, boringly, as a psychiatrist, a lot of work that I have done is helping people to see for themselves what it is they need to do.

48:01.000 --> 48:08.000
And that, you know, if you make the mistake, as when I was wet behind the ears and haven't had a lot of experience in psychology,

48:08.000 --> 48:13.000
I used to do it just to tell people what they needed to do. It wasn't that I was wrong. I was right.

48:13.000 --> 48:17.000
But the thing is, it's no good telling people until they see it for themselves.

48:17.000 --> 48:22.000
And what's more, what they will see is greater than anything. I can tell them and more appropriate to them.

48:22.000 --> 48:30.000
So that's what I'd say. I mean, of course, I can become banal and say there are things to do, like practice mindfulness, which I think is very important.

48:31.000 --> 48:42.000
Practice being compassionate and grateful. These are simple things and listen more to music and attend to it.

48:42.000 --> 48:46.000
Don't just, you know, have it on in the background and not pay attention to it.

48:46.000 --> 48:54.000
So, and to read myths and re-engage really with a mythology.

48:54.000 --> 48:58.000
And the best mythologies are religious mythologies, in my view.

48:58.000 --> 49:03.000
I mean, they're the accumulation of wisdom with so many people over so long.

49:03.000 --> 49:11.000
The idea that little me can in my lifetime with a little bit that I know improve on that is hubris, isn't it?

49:11.000 --> 49:15.000
Isn't that just an extraordinary act of arrogance?

49:15.000 --> 49:22.000
So it's not to say that, you know, traditions aren't changing. They're changing all the time. They flow.

49:22.000 --> 49:29.000
But the only way in which we can make things go in the direction that we think is better is by engaging with that tradition.

49:29.000 --> 49:35.000
It's like a plug that you want to go somewhere. You don't cut it off from its stem and roots and stick it on the wall.

49:35.000 --> 49:38.000
You train it there, and that's what a tradition is like.

49:38.000 --> 49:45.000
That's very cool. I think maybe I can push on that a bit.

49:45.000 --> 49:54.000
So I think for people today, there is a great difficulty engaging with these religious traditions,

49:54.000 --> 50:03.000
which I would say are kind of the great mythos, mythoses of our civilization.

50:03.000 --> 50:05.000
Yeah, mythos.

50:05.000 --> 50:12.000
So I think we're engaging instead with what you might call a synthetic mythos.

50:12.000 --> 50:20.000
And two of the great figures in that happening. One is Joseph Campbell and his hero's journey or his mono myth.

50:20.000 --> 50:29.000
So I would say it's kind of like a synthesizing. He takes all of this pattern from great mythic traditions,

50:29.000 --> 50:39.000
especially the Christian tradition, and presents it as a pattern which is then picked up by storytellers,

50:39.000 --> 50:43.000
famously Star Wars, but hundreds of other movies.

50:43.000 --> 50:50.000
And these movies seem to be consistently very powerful for people. They have a real effect.

50:50.000 --> 50:59.000
And then Campbell's ideas are really coming from Carl Jung and his ideas about archetypes and so on.

50:59.000 --> 51:07.000
So could you comment perhaps a bit on the idea of could a synthetic mythos have value in that way,

51:07.000 --> 51:17.000
and also about perhaps a relationship between Jung and your own thinking on the hemispheres and meaning of myth?

51:17.000 --> 51:27.000
Yes, there is a very strong link between my thinking and Jung, and it really wasn't from reading Jung that I generated what I think.

51:27.000 --> 51:33.000
It worked the other way that I worked from the neuroscience to see what the picture was.

51:33.000 --> 51:40.000
And it wasn't always the one that people would anticipate. And yet I found constantly resonances with Jung's work.

51:40.000 --> 51:47.000
And with Hillman, you know, James Hillman, who was a disciple, if you like, of Jung.

51:47.000 --> 51:58.000
So yes, no, I agree with this. What I found is that myths I from all around the world have similar core perceptions.

51:58.000 --> 52:09.000
At the beginning of part three of The Matter with Things, which is the section on ontology or metaphysics, whatever you like to call it.

52:09.000 --> 52:21.000
And I quote at some length a myth of the Onondaga people who are Iroquois, which I think is staggering.

52:21.000 --> 52:28.000
I mean, when I first heard it, I could not believe it. It was absolutely what I was seeing in the hemispheres.

52:28.000 --> 52:35.000
It's the story of two brothers, one of which is more insightful and better motivated than the other.

52:35.000 --> 52:44.000
But they both have divine power. And what needs to happen is that the one that is more fallible and more arrogant and more resentful,

52:44.000 --> 52:50.000
this other brother, is kept, if you like, under the aegis of the wise brother.

52:50.000 --> 52:57.000
But they shouldn't get too close together, because otherwise what the right hemisphere, the master, the better brother sees,

52:57.000 --> 53:00.000
would be initiated by what the left hemisphere contributes.

53:01.000 --> 53:07.000
And so that was a staggering one. But, you know, people don't have to espouse Christianity.

53:07.000 --> 53:14.000
I happen to think it's the richest of all the mythologies. But there's so much in Vedanta. There's so much in Taoism.

53:14.000 --> 53:23.000
I'm a Taoist. And there's no contradiction between being a Taoist and being, in my case, a very odd and probably not very good Christian.

53:23.000 --> 53:38.000
But at least these are other ways of thinking that it's so rich that it's like them is to deprive yourself of all the things that to me seem to give life its richness.

53:38.000 --> 53:47.000
So I hope people will rediscover it. And I think, although you say people are very resistant to this, I think they're resistant to the bad stuff.

53:48.000 --> 53:55.000
And particularly when they look at religions as a fundamentalist and violent and hateful, that has nothing to do with religion.

53:55.000 --> 54:02.000
Nothing. So, I mean, that's just a perversion of religion. There's a horrible exagressiveness from a religion.

54:02.000 --> 54:10.000
But they are searching for myths, but not just the sort of myth that somebody made up yesterday, really.

54:10.000 --> 54:16.000
But one that seems to reflect a deep insight into the nature of the cosmos.

54:16.000 --> 54:28.000
And sometimes this can be done in less mythical terms. I mean, I hope that what I have, if you like, I certainly don't want to go on record of saying that I think the hemisphere differences is a myth,

54:28.000 --> 54:33.000
except in the sense that this can be profoundly true in a logical way as well.

54:33.000 --> 54:41.000
But it is, if you like, a helpful myth that enables people to see why certain things go together, you know.

54:41.000 --> 54:53.000
Why, for example, would an attention to detail a failure to understand implicit meaning and a kind of insane optimism go together?

54:53.000 --> 55:01.000
I mean, they don't sound like they should. But in fact, if you know about hemisphere differences, you can see exactly why they don't.

55:01.000 --> 55:05.000
And then you can start seeing it in, I just put those three randomly together.

55:05.000 --> 55:09.000
Because after all, there are so many differences, you can find many intersections.

55:09.000 --> 55:21.000
But all I'm really saying is that the old vision of the right and left was just so wrong, and we need to really pay attention critically to what the real differences are if we're to know ourselves.

55:21.000 --> 55:30.000
And you know, the great injunction of the ancient Greek world was know thyself. It's very simple, too worse, but so profound.

55:30.000 --> 55:37.000
I think my before encountering your ideas, and they helped me to understand this much more clearly.

55:37.000 --> 55:45.000
My way into some of this was through attempting to be creative, trying to write for me.

55:45.000 --> 55:52.000
And then quite young, actually, I started teaching writing.

55:52.000 --> 55:59.000
And one of the groups of people I would work with were people who were very intelligent, usually professionals.

55:59.000 --> 56:09.000
They were now retired professionals. So they had a very highly trained intellect, and they were trying to crack this nut of being creative.

56:09.000 --> 56:27.000
And I came up with my own myth about it, which I would use with people, which is that the part of you that wants to be creative is like a crazy old hippie that has huge ideas, often about myths, actually.

56:27.000 --> 56:42.000
But in order to express it, you have to work with, you have to get the crazy old hippie to work with a kind of uptight middle manager who actually has the writing skills that are needed to do the writing.

56:42.000 --> 56:49.000
And you have to somehow get these two characters into a room together and get them working together.

56:50.000 --> 56:57.000
Which I think for me is something like the left and right hemispheres in their character.

56:57.000 --> 57:11.000
But I feel that for a lot of people, their way into this is about this creative challenge. Like you try and write, but there's this inner editor who's always there criticising everything that you write.

57:11.000 --> 57:14.000
So you never finish anything.

57:14.000 --> 57:24.000
Well, just as I said, that's been a big problem in my life. I have a very strong inner critic.

57:24.000 --> 57:32.000
But I think the only thing I'd have to do here is to dissociate myself from the idea that the right hemisphere is a crazy old hippie.

57:32.000 --> 57:41.000
The right hemisphere is the fount of wisdom, really. And it's also very down to earth, by the way, unlike many hippies.

57:41.000 --> 57:49.000
It is actually the one that is more in touch with reality and better grounded than the left, which goes off on fantasies.

57:49.000 --> 58:01.000
But what I would add to your picture is that when people want to be creative, they're wanting to be creative is something to be slightly wary of.

58:01.000 --> 58:09.000
Because it's one of those things that can't be wanted in a left hemisphere way. So what do I do? I follow the following steps.

58:09.000 --> 58:20.000
And that is not going to work any more than I want to believe, you know, really work. And you can try. It's true.

58:20.000 --> 58:30.000
But in a way, you have to open yourself up to something that you don't yet know what it is. And in order to do that, you have to still the part of your mind that is striving to achieve.

58:30.000 --> 58:41.000
This part of your mind that says, I know what it is. I know what I need. Because every time we say, I know, we close down again on the familiar that we're trying to get away from.

58:41.000 --> 58:52.000
And so a lot of time in creation passes in what appears to be unfruitful openness to things without any conclusions being drawn.

58:52.000 --> 59:05.000
But it's only in that wise silence of not saying and not doing that things will begin to reveal themselves to us.

59:05.000 --> 59:18.000
Steiner has written very well, George Steiner, on this idea of the sort of attentive mind that is hearing something. It's not quite clear yet, but it's leaning into it.

59:18.000 --> 59:32.000
And that is a very good model, which he sees actually imaged in the four paintings of the Annunciation by Fra Angelica, in which the Virgin is sort of listening to the angel.

59:32.000 --> 59:40.000
And the angel is sort of as if we're attending to the Virgin. Anyway.

59:41.000 --> 59:50.000
Yeah, and just just sitting with some of that for a moment. When you said about your own inner critic.

59:50.000 --> 59:51.000
Yes.

59:51.000 --> 01:00:03.000
Have you do you feel that in the writing of nonfiction of these two books that you have you have silenced the critic to some extent.

01:00:03.000 --> 01:00:15.000
I was curious when I can. The critic is usually most vocal and I'm trying to get started, which is a sort of catch 22.

01:00:15.000 --> 01:00:23.000
And in fact, I only was able to write the master and his emissary by pretending to myself. And I really did believe that's what I was doing.

01:00:23.000 --> 01:00:36.000
Okay. I wrote all the main concepts about 70 of them on little lozenges of paper and I laid them all out on the floor in the living room and moved them about to see where they went and see if I could find a diagram.

01:00:36.000 --> 01:00:46.000
I really couldn't. So I said to myself, right, I'm no more than 25 pages, a skeleton of where you want to be going in this book.

01:00:46.000 --> 01:00:54.000
And I headed it up as you can, of course, in word with the header that said draft out time of the master and his emissary.

01:00:54.000 --> 01:01:06.000
And it finally reached about 1300 pages of text. And I printed it off and gave it to a friend of mine who I call my unofficial editor because he's so insightful.

01:01:06.000 --> 01:01:14.000
And he had a shop. I gave it to him in a shopping bag and he looked at it and he saw the title and he said, some odd lie.

01:01:14.000 --> 01:01:19.000
And indeed it was, but that was the way in which I sort of fooled myself into writing it.

01:01:19.000 --> 01:01:32.000
But another thing is that I feel that when I'm writing well, stuff comes from that place, which is not entirely forced or intended.

01:01:32.000 --> 01:01:44.000
Stuff asks me to be written. And I sometimes thought when I looked at the master's emissary and even more when I looked at the matter with things,

01:01:44.000 --> 01:01:53.000
which as you know is an even greater task in terms of the amount of scholarship and science in it.

01:01:53.000 --> 01:02:00.000
I sort of look at it and think, but how did you write that? I mean, you're a lazy person. How could you have written it?

01:02:00.000 --> 01:02:09.000
So I have a conclusion that the mice wrote it in the night. The Taylor of Gloucester came down in the morning, not having enough gloss to the waistcoat.

01:02:09.000 --> 01:02:16.000
He had to deliver in the morning and suddenly found the mice had made it. I feel not like that.

01:02:16.000 --> 01:02:22.000
You see, the thing is that very little of what goes on is conscious. We have this idea that there are two tanks.

01:02:22.000 --> 01:02:38.000
There's a sort of nice, big, clear tank of consciousness. And underneath is a slightly murky, muddy region, which has a sort of, perhaps a sort of flip column through which you can pass from one to the other.

01:02:38.000 --> 01:02:42.000
But most of what goes on is in the consciousness. This is absolutely not true.

01:02:42.000 --> 01:02:59.000
I mean, I used to say that 95% of all our mental activity is unconscious, but a paper with rather amusing precision that I quote in the book says that 99.44% for mental activity is not conscious.

01:02:59.000 --> 01:03:08.000
In other words, you don't have to buy the precision to get the point that almost everything we do and not just the sort of lesser stuff goes on unconsciously.

01:03:08.000 --> 01:03:23.000
So we solve difficult problems in maths in our life. We project how to deal with the future to make decisions to like things, to fall in love, to not.

01:03:23.000 --> 01:03:30.000
All these things are going on under the radar and they're not unintelligent for that. They're using our full intelligence.

01:03:30.000 --> 01:03:42.000
And you found a very, for a work of very, based on a lot of very rigorous research, you found a very potent myth to communicate.

01:03:42.000 --> 01:03:43.000
Yes.

01:03:43.000 --> 01:03:57.000
In the master and the master and his emissary, which I think is why it has communicated because this seems to be a very important part of communicating complex ideas to people.

01:03:57.000 --> 01:03:58.000
Yes.

01:03:58.000 --> 01:04:12.000
I think, for instance, like Einsteinian relativity is completely incomprehensible to most people, but the idea that you go to space and you come back and it's the future because of relativity.

01:04:12.000 --> 01:04:19.000
That is the myth that people can actually get onto or the trains in relation to each other.

01:04:19.000 --> 01:04:20.000
Yes.

01:04:20.000 --> 01:04:25.000
What you're describing is quite a consistent story of myth makers.

01:04:25.000 --> 01:04:26.000
Yes.

01:04:26.000 --> 01:04:34.000
That this comes from somewhere beyond us, from artists and creators and scientists as well.

01:04:34.000 --> 01:04:41.000
Anyone who reaches that real insight, it seems to come from beyond us.

01:04:41.000 --> 01:04:49.000
So is that beyond the right hemisphere or is that simplifying too much?

01:04:49.000 --> 01:04:59.000
I think that could be simplifying too much.

01:04:59.000 --> 01:05:05.000
The thing is we don't know, really, the depths of our knowledge because if we did, we'd be conscious of it.

01:05:05.000 --> 01:05:16.000
But I think that in our unconscious, we are making sense of clocking and understanding intuitively something about the way our mind and therefore our brain works.

01:05:16.000 --> 01:05:23.000
And for me, the best demonstration of this is this Onondaga legend, which is completely amazing.

01:05:23.000 --> 01:05:27.000
It's so accurate about how the train actually works.

01:05:27.000 --> 01:05:33.000
And it comes from an era before there were any brain imaging studies.

01:05:33.000 --> 01:05:38.000
So I think that's the way I put it.

01:05:38.000 --> 01:05:50.000
The difficulty with the myth is that people who are very, if you like, narrow in their thinking think that if he's created a thing that submits, it must be wrong.

01:05:50.000 --> 01:05:52.000
He's not a real scientist.

01:05:52.000 --> 01:05:57.000
This is rather a shame because I've really sweated blood over the science.

01:05:57.000 --> 01:06:03.000
And I defy anyone to show me exactly why I've got this wrong and nobody ever has.

01:06:03.000 --> 01:06:07.000
In fact, there's a very interesting phenomenon, which is something like this.

01:06:07.000 --> 01:06:13.000
Scientists say, well, I love the neuroscience and no quarrel with that.

01:06:13.000 --> 01:06:15.000
It's very interesting and revealing.

01:06:15.000 --> 01:06:18.000
But then you go on and apply it to life.

01:06:18.000 --> 01:06:20.000
And I'm not with you there.

01:06:20.000 --> 01:06:24.000
And then there are other people who say, well, I don't know about the neuroscience and so on.

01:06:24.000 --> 01:06:30.000
But what you see in the evolution of Western culture is so right.

01:06:30.000 --> 01:06:33.000
You know, it just cries out.

01:06:33.000 --> 01:06:37.000
So you've got these two people, each of them sort of saying, yes, this bit is fine, this bit.

01:06:37.000 --> 01:06:41.000
They don't want a corpus callatum to put them together.

01:06:41.000 --> 01:06:46.000
But that's what I hope I have provided because they do need to be seen together.

01:06:46.000 --> 01:06:50.000
And my editor at Yale for the Master in Science, I sort of said, you know, I think there are two books here.

01:06:50.000 --> 01:06:52.000
We could make two books out of this.

01:06:52.000 --> 01:06:56.000
And she very wisely said, yeah, but the trouble is that the scientists would read one

01:06:56.000 --> 01:07:00.000
and the humanities people would read the other and never the train should meet.

01:07:00.000 --> 01:07:05.000
And so I'm extremely glad that she insisted they should all be part of one book.

01:07:05.000 --> 01:07:08.000
Can I ask you about the idea of the machine?

01:07:08.000 --> 01:07:09.000
Absolutely.

01:07:09.000 --> 01:07:13.000
Again, because this is very powerful in science fiction.

01:07:13.000 --> 01:07:14.000
Yes.

01:07:14.000 --> 01:07:18.000
We have from Frankenstein.

01:07:18.000 --> 01:07:22.000
So Mary Shelley's Frankenstein written in the Gothic tradition,

01:07:22.000 --> 01:07:25.000
but it's often recognized as the first science fiction.

01:07:25.000 --> 01:07:26.000
Yes.

01:07:26.000 --> 01:07:30.000
You of course have a scientist at the heart of it.

01:07:30.000 --> 01:07:37.000
And but then this idea that you can put together a body from spare parts.

01:07:37.000 --> 01:07:45.000
That if we've given up the idea of humans as some kind of divine entity, perhaps with a soul,

01:07:45.000 --> 01:07:47.000
what do we say they are?

01:07:47.000 --> 01:07:50.000
So we start to say that we're machines.

01:07:50.000 --> 01:07:58.000
And Shelley reflects on that and reflects on the kind of the horror of that possibility.

01:07:58.000 --> 01:08:05.000
A very famous science fiction movie like The Matrix where we're literally lost in machines

01:08:05.000 --> 01:08:07.000
that control every part of our life.

01:08:07.000 --> 01:08:13.000
And this is something I talk with about two of my podcast listeners.

01:08:13.000 --> 01:08:17.000
Because I'd say about 70 percent of the science fiction community.

01:08:17.000 --> 01:08:18.000
And I pull them on this.

01:08:18.000 --> 01:08:21.000
If I asked them would say, yes, I am a machine.

01:08:21.000 --> 01:08:28.000
And they might add to that that I am a biological, a biological machine.

01:08:28.000 --> 01:08:32.000
So this seems to be the mythos of our time.

01:08:32.000 --> 01:08:36.000
This is how we understand ourselves now as a machine.

01:08:36.000 --> 01:08:42.000
And I know that that you can can see through that or pass that for us.

01:08:42.000 --> 01:08:53.000
And I'd like you maybe to talk to my listeners who think that they are machines about how to have a larger picture of ourselves and that.

01:08:53.000 --> 01:09:00.000
Well, in chapter 12 of The Matter With Things, a chapter called The Science of Life.

01:09:00.000 --> 01:09:04.000
A case of left hemisphere capture.

01:09:04.000 --> 01:09:11.000
What I'm arguing there is that organisms are holes that are not decomposable into their parts

01:09:11.000 --> 01:09:14.000
and are not understood if viewed as machines.

01:09:14.000 --> 01:09:21.000
And that's not anything I say without serious scientific evidence.

01:09:21.000 --> 01:09:28.000
And there are a number of talks I've now done, perhaps half a dozen, with Michael Levin,

01:09:28.000 --> 01:09:39.000
who is a distinguished professor at Tufts and a microbiologist and geneticist and evolutionary biologist about this.

01:09:39.000 --> 01:09:50.000
And I think that more and more I see people realizing that the old story that was told that we were all, you know, this sort of...

01:09:50.000 --> 01:09:56.000
I'm poor at talking, but this idea that somehow, you know, we're lumbering robots controlled by our genes for their benefits.

01:09:56.000 --> 01:10:04.000
And that was a myth that was simply mythical in the pejorative sense.

01:10:04.000 --> 01:10:13.000
And that we are not machines. And we could completely miss many things and can't explain many things if we think of ourselves as that.

01:10:13.000 --> 01:10:19.000
I think I give at least eight ways in which we differ from machines and look over the evidence in some detail.

01:10:19.000 --> 01:10:23.000
So I recommend people to read it if they're interested.

01:10:23.000 --> 01:10:32.000
But I think there's a big problem here, which is more of a philosophical nature, that we don't understand the relationship between parts and the whole.

01:10:32.000 --> 01:10:36.000
And what I think is that parts are an invention.

01:10:36.000 --> 01:10:51.000
So what that is holds, in other words, not mechanical constructions, but non-divisible, although they have distinguishable parts,

01:10:51.000 --> 01:10:55.000
but non-divisible holds that can't be reduced to that part.

01:10:55.000 --> 01:11:06.000
And there was a great mathematician and philosopher called Robert Rosen, who wrote a book called Life Itself,

01:11:06.000 --> 01:11:16.000
and a more approachable book called Essays on Life Itself, in which he argues that whatever exists is largely better understood

01:11:16.000 --> 01:11:23.000
by assimilating it to the model of an organism than that of a machine, even the inanimate world.

01:11:23.000 --> 01:11:29.000
And he leads to the conclusion that actually, inanimacy is something that doesn't really exist,

01:11:29.000 --> 01:11:38.000
but would be the asymptotically approached reality if one pushed the mechanical idea far enough.

01:11:38.000 --> 01:11:40.000
But it doesn't actually exist anymore.

01:11:40.000 --> 01:11:44.000
And that when one starts realizing what one's dealing with is organic holds,

01:11:44.000 --> 01:11:51.000
one understands their behavior and the way in which we understand them, we understand them much better.

01:11:51.000 --> 01:12:00.000
So all that exists is holds, and what we see as parts are holds at another level.

01:12:00.000 --> 01:12:05.000
And so there are, in a sense, a nesting of holds in the cosmos.

01:12:05.000 --> 01:12:13.000
And different holds are appropriate at different levels of magnification, if you like, to talk in those terms.

01:12:13.000 --> 01:12:22.000
So that's some of what I'd say, but I could quote some fascinating things that suggest that we're not.

01:12:22.000 --> 01:12:27.000
Barbara Matintock, who won a Nobel Prize for her work in microbiology,

01:12:27.000 --> 01:12:37.000
was able to show that microorganisms, bacteria, and single cells were able to respond in an imaginative way to a crisis

01:12:37.000 --> 01:12:42.000
that they were never programmed to tackle and had never experienced before.

01:12:42.000 --> 01:12:47.000
But they came up with a solution nonetheless, and that requires a certain kind of intelligence.

01:12:47.000 --> 01:12:52.000
Whatever you like to say, it might not be intelligence like yours or mine, but it's some kind of an intelligence.

01:12:52.000 --> 01:12:56.000
And there are many other instances throughout the natural world,

01:12:56.000 --> 01:13:01.000
that plants that make decisions that they simply can't possibly have been prepared for

01:13:01.000 --> 01:13:06.000
in strange situations set up in the laboratory, probably haven't got time to explain them here,

01:13:06.000 --> 01:13:09.000
but they are ripping and amazing.

01:13:09.000 --> 01:13:15.000
So we know that all that lives, and probably all the things that we don't think live,

01:13:15.000 --> 01:13:18.000
behave in ways that we haven't completely fathomed.

01:13:18.000 --> 01:13:26.000
And as you go further and further into the ultramicroscopic world of particle physics and so on,

01:13:26.000 --> 01:13:30.000
you realize that once again the idea of a mechanism doesn't work.

01:13:30.000 --> 01:13:37.000
So the way I look at it is the idea of a mechanism is a kind of shoddy model

01:13:37.000 --> 01:13:42.000
that works okay for practical purposes in the middle of something,

01:13:42.000 --> 01:13:45.000
but it doesn't work at all when you go small or go big,

01:13:45.000 --> 01:13:49.000
and it doesn't work at all when you go in rather than out.

01:13:49.000 --> 01:13:55.000
So as I sometimes say, if I were building a garage, I don't need to take into account the curvature of the world,

01:13:55.000 --> 01:13:57.000
but that doesn't mean the world is flat.

01:13:57.000 --> 01:14:02.000
The world is curved, and it's spherical, and that's really important to note.

01:14:02.000 --> 01:14:07.000
But for certain purposes one can ignore reality, and the left hemisphere's model is not real.

01:14:07.000 --> 01:14:12.000
It's a model, exactly that, and a machine is simply a model.

01:14:12.000 --> 01:14:16.000
It's a way in which we have modeled things in order to be able to manipulate the world better.

01:14:16.000 --> 01:14:23.000
And for those purposes they work, but a mistake is to think that because we've made something that works,

01:14:23.000 --> 01:14:29.000
we understand the things of which it is only a remote cousin,

01:14:29.000 --> 01:14:33.000
or not even that because it doesn't belong to the same family at all.

01:14:33.000 --> 01:14:37.000
Could we almost argue then that there aren't any machines?

01:14:37.000 --> 01:14:45.000
A machine is when we impose this map onto something which is actually a set of holes,

01:14:45.000 --> 01:14:51.000
and we see it as a machine because we're going to use it for a certain purpose.

01:14:51.000 --> 01:14:58.000
Yes, all the ways in which we understand things are models, and we improve the model or we don't.

01:14:58.000 --> 01:15:06.000
And I think the model of the machine, yes, it works very well every day for making stuff to help us manipulate.

01:15:06.000 --> 01:15:14.000
But it's not truthful, it's just a model, not a very good one, not a very sophisticated one, but it's fine.

01:15:14.000 --> 01:15:20.000
And the proof of the pudding is that it has made us powerful, alas, without improving our wisdom.

01:15:20.000 --> 01:15:26.000
And I would say we're probably the least wise people that have ever inhabited the earth, and yet we're also the most powerful.

01:15:26.000 --> 01:15:32.000
This is a dangerous combination.

01:15:32.000 --> 01:15:39.000
And we tell this story in myth over and over again that our machines are very powerful, but they're not wise.

01:15:39.000 --> 01:15:49.000
And they're unable to wield meaningful, to create meaningful things in the world.

01:15:49.000 --> 01:15:52.000
They will strip meaning out of everything.

01:15:52.000 --> 01:15:57.000
But it seems very, I just want to push on it a little bit further.

01:15:57.000 --> 01:16:05.000
It seems very, very, very sad that so many people see ourselves.

01:16:05.000 --> 01:16:12.000
So certainly, probably up until my mid-twenties, I would have agreed with that assertion that I am a machine.

01:16:12.000 --> 01:16:18.000
And I feel sad about that in retrospect for what I may have thought about myself.

01:16:18.000 --> 01:16:27.000
And I think it was also accompanied with a lot of other thoughts, a certain despair, if the world is just a big machine.

01:16:27.000 --> 01:16:32.000
Where is the meaning in any of this for me?

01:16:32.000 --> 01:16:40.000
Well, yes, and you referred to images coming from the early 20th century.

01:16:40.000 --> 01:16:47.000
And one that you probably know is the machine stops a short story by Am Forster, which is amazing.

01:16:47.000 --> 01:16:54.000
He saw already in 1912, whenever he wrote it, that we were going to be ending up basically living in a machine depending on it,

01:16:54.000 --> 01:16:56.000
and not really understanding what lay outside it.

01:16:56.000 --> 01:16:58.000
So it is a worry.

01:16:58.000 --> 01:17:04.000
But, you know, can a machine bleed?

01:17:04.000 --> 01:17:07.000
To quote Bertrand de Venis.

01:17:07.000 --> 01:17:10.000
Can a machine sorrow?

01:17:10.000 --> 01:17:12.000
Can it fall in love?

01:17:12.000 --> 01:17:14.000
Can it change its mind?

01:17:14.000 --> 01:17:17.000
Can it truly imagine?

01:17:17.000 --> 01:17:22.000
In what ways is a machine like us?

01:17:22.000 --> 01:17:30.000
All that we do in AI is to project outwards a bloodless, abstracted way of thinking.

01:17:30.000 --> 01:17:40.000
Turning something that is something we should be trying to get beyond, not enlarged.

01:17:40.000 --> 01:17:49.000
And it is the means whereby the left hemisphere's thinking is pushed outwards into the world.

01:17:49.000 --> 01:17:57.000
You see, because the left hemisphere loves the theory, it prefers anything that fits with the theory and doesn't see anything that doesn't fit with its theory.

01:17:57.000 --> 01:18:04.000
So once you've decided that people are machines, for example, just to take an example, then you don't see all the evidence of things that don't fit with them.

01:18:04.000 --> 01:18:08.000
Because the left hemisphere wants consistency with its model.

01:18:08.000 --> 01:18:13.000
The right hemisphere is what V.S. Ramachandran, a very great neuroscientist, called the devil's advocate.

01:18:13.000 --> 01:18:16.000
In other words, it says, yeah, but hang on, it might not be like that.

01:18:16.000 --> 01:18:23.000
That says it's a really important element to have in one's armory.

01:18:23.000 --> 01:18:30.000
And the right hemisphere's way of approaching things is, okay, you say this in theory.

01:18:30.000 --> 01:18:34.000
Let's now test it against reality.

01:18:34.000 --> 01:18:41.000
Now, that's great, but the difficulty is that the left hemisphere has colonized external reality.

01:18:41.000 --> 01:18:47.000
So for many people, when they look outwards into the world, they see a screen, they see a machine, they see...

01:18:47.000 --> 01:18:56.000
All around them, they see a bringing into being of this mechanical, utilitarian world, which is the left hemisphere's world.

01:18:56.000 --> 01:19:02.000
And in recent years, it has pushed forward in two very damaging ways.

01:19:02.000 --> 01:19:13.000
One is a colossal growth, like a cancer of administration, so that now all the institutions that look after us and look after our future,

01:19:13.000 --> 01:19:24.000
the universities, the schools, the hospitals are top-heavy with departments of management that try to tell teachers and doctors and lecturers

01:19:24.000 --> 01:19:28.000
what they should say and what they should do and who they should hire.

01:19:28.000 --> 01:19:31.000
And this is a very bad state of affairs.

01:19:31.000 --> 01:19:37.000
It's an expression outwards of left hemisphere procedural thinking, and the other is AI.

01:19:37.000 --> 01:19:42.000
And now so much of time is wasted for all of us by machines.

01:19:42.000 --> 01:19:47.000
So something that ten years ago would have taken a five-minute phone call to somebody in the office who said,

01:19:47.000 --> 01:19:49.000
I see what's going on, don't worry, I can sort that.

01:19:49.000 --> 01:19:54.000
But now I spend literally half a day on the internet, and instead of being able to speak to somebody, it says,

01:19:54.000 --> 01:19:56.000
you know, we can help you.

01:19:56.000 --> 01:20:01.000
I frequently ask questions, but the frequently asked questions are never the ones I'm really asking,

01:20:01.000 --> 01:20:04.000
because they're too generic and I've got a typical problem here.

01:20:04.000 --> 01:20:09.000
And, you know, there are boxes you have to check and things you have to go through to get there,

01:20:09.000 --> 01:20:13.000
and I can't because nothing is truthful in response to them.

01:20:13.000 --> 01:20:15.000
So this is a huge waste of time.

01:20:15.000 --> 01:20:21.000
And you might, I don't know if I've got time just very briefly to refer to an amusing episode in recent history

01:20:21.000 --> 01:20:26.000
when I gave a lecture for Oxford University and much of my amazement was paid for it.

01:20:26.000 --> 01:20:28.000
It's delightful, it's rather handsomely paid for it.

01:20:28.000 --> 01:20:33.000
And in the old days what would have happened is that the finance department called the University Chess

01:20:33.000 --> 01:20:36.000
would have sent me a check in the post and I'd have cashed it.

01:20:36.000 --> 01:20:41.000
But no, now lots of things have to be done through a platform online.

01:20:41.000 --> 01:20:47.000
And not only one, but a couple of platforms, and you can only graduate to the second one once you've done the first.

01:20:47.000 --> 01:20:50.000
And they said, don't worry, we've got someone who will guide you through this.

01:20:50.000 --> 01:20:54.000
Three months into this process, not having got onto the second platform,

01:20:54.000 --> 01:20:57.000
the person moved on to another job.

01:20:57.000 --> 01:20:59.000
They said, don't worry, somebody else is coming.

01:20:59.000 --> 01:21:04.000
Six months into this process, this other person and I had not been able to solve the problem.

01:21:04.000 --> 01:21:07.000
And eventually I thought, what the hell is going on here?

01:21:07.000 --> 01:21:10.000
Because it asked me to tick a box, and there were 77 boxes,

